255
00:19:52,280 --> 00:19:53,780
Good to see you.

256
00:19:54,050 --> 00:19:56,680
Madiba. Madiba. Madiba!

257
00:19:57,060 --> 00:19:58,810
You're delaying the rugby, sir.

258
00:19:58,860 --> 00:20:00,530
Oh, yes, of course.

259
00:20:14,060 --> 00:20:16,910
- Why didn't you stop him?
- Well. You try next time.

260
00:20:16,960 --> 00:20:18,750
Does he do that sort of thing
all the time?

261
00:20:18,800 --> 00:20:20,300
Ask my ulcer.

262
00:20:20,580 --> 00:20:24,030
- Good thing it was just a cup.
- And good thing he never saw it.

263
00:20:24,080 --> 00:20:26,380
Oh, he saw it. He sees everything.

264
00:20:26,600 --> 00:20:28,100
I hate rugby.

265
00:20:28,880 --> 00:20:31,660
- Yay!
- "That's right"

266
00:20:42,600 --> 00:20:45,120
With you. With you. Keep on running.
Outside . Outside. Come on.

267
00:20:45,170 --> 00:20:46,290
Come on.

268
00:20:53,490 --> 00:20:58,570
<i>...Team England scored...</i>

269
00:20:58,970 --> 00:21:00,250
<i>England, 11</i>

270
00:21:00,360 --> 00:21:03,010
<i>South Africa, 0</i>

271
00:21:06,430 --> 00:21:09,280
These English mean business.
We need to focus!

272
00:21:10,410 --> 00:21:12,660
Come on. We need to focus. Focus!

273
00:21:14,640 --> 00:21:16,190
Come on.

274
00:21:28,490 --> 00:21:31,190
Why don't we do a little work
while we watch.

275
00:21:31,240 --> 00:21:32,900
We have a lot of promises to keep.

276
00:21:32,950 --> 00:21:34,450
Yes, we do.

277
00:21:41,020 --> 00:21:42,560
It's not too late,

278
00:21:42,650 --> 00:21:45,250
if the boys can just pick up their game.

279
00:21:45,890 --> 00:21:48,040
If they don't, heads will roll.

280
00:21:51,130 --> 00:21:53,200
C'mon you bloody bastards!

281
00:22:02,390 --> 00:22:05,040
Where do you want go first,
for foreign investment?

282
00:22:05,090 --> 00:22:06,640
Where the money is.

283
00:22:06,690 --> 00:22:10,260
America, England, Saudi Arabia.

284
00:22:16,240 --> 00:22:18,340
How long before the World Cup?

285
00:22:19,130 --> 00:22:20,660
About a year.

286
00:22:22,060 --> 00:22:24,560
Now, it's time enough for
improvement.

287
00:22:25,860 --> 00:22:27,730
Mr. President...

288
00:22:28,500 --> 00:22:30,450
...I wouldn't get my hopes up.

289
00:22:30,980 --> 00:22:32,680
We're a damn disgrace.

290
00:22:38,420 --> 00:22:41,070
Do you see all those old
apartheid flags?

291
00:22:42,230 --> 00:22:43,730
It's a disgrace.

292
00:22:43,810 --> 00:22:46,120
It's also a constitutional right.

293
00:22:46,770 --> 00:22:49,370
Along with the apartheid anthem. I know.

294
00:22:50,110 --> 00:22:52,530
But it's time people moved on.

295
00:22:55,680 --> 00:22:57,180
Look at this.

296
00:22:58,120 --> 00:23:01,170
All of the whites are cheering
for the Springboks.

297
00:23:02,390 --> 00:23:05,090
All of the blacks are cheering
for England.

299
00:23:08,610 --> 00:23:10,960
I used to do that on the island.

300
00:23:11,180 --> 00:23:13,830
We would cheer for anyone
but the 'boks.

301
00:23:14,750 --> 00:23:16,900
It made warders very angry.

302
00:23:17,310 --> 00:23:18,810
Of course it did.

303
00:23:22,700 --> 00:23:24,990
Sorry I'm late, how's it going?

304
00:23:25,220 --> 00:23:26,690
Very badly.

305
00:23:31,790 --> 00:23:33,590
Maybe it's just as well.

306
00:23:34,400 --> 00:23:35,420
Why?

307
00:23:37,540 --> 00:23:41,540
I've just been at a meeting of
the National Sports executive.

308
00:23:43,400 --> 00:23:45,930
There's strong support to drop
the Springbok emblem

309
00:23:45,980 --> 00:23:47,890
and colors altogether

310
00:23:48,210 --> 00:23:50,410
If they're playing badly.

311
00:23:51,180 --> 00:23:53,780
Maybe it's a good time to make a change.

312
00:23:54,420 --> 00:23:58,270
This could be the last time we have
to look at the green and gold.

313
00:24:18,710 --> 00:24:19,700
Shit.

314
00:24:37,440 --> 00:24:40,500
<i>Francois Pienaar's team came
to Loftus Versfeld stadium</i>

315
00:24:40,550 --> 00:24:41,750
<i>this afternoon,</i>

316
00:24:41,800 --> 00:24:43,600
<i>unprepared and arrogant.</i>

317
00:24:44,890 --> 00:24:48,870
They left 80 minutes later with
their tails between their legs,

318
00:24:48,910 --> 00:24:50,610
like whipped mongrels.

319
00:24:50,740 --> 00:24:52,730
And I, for one, am glad.

320
00:24:53,590 --> 00:24:58,970
Not because they lost, but because
there's now no way to ignore the fact

321
00:24:59,170 --> 00:25:02,090
that we are completely
and utterly unprepared

322
00:25:02,140 --> 00:25:05,440
<i>to reenter the world of top-notch
international rugby.</i>

323
00:25:06,740 --> 00:25:09,900
<i>The Rugby World Cup is now
less than a year away,</i>

324
00:25:10,150 --> 00:25:13,340
<i>and I, for one, am relieved
that we are the host nation,</i>

325
00:25:13,390 --> 00:25:15,980
<i>and therefore qualified automatically
for the tournament.</i>

326
00:25:16,030 --> 00:25:17,140
Somebody gets the axe.

327
00:25:17,190 --> 00:25:20,760
<i>Because I'm not sure that we would
get in on merit alone.</i>

328
00:25:20,990 --> 00:25:22,490
Who's it gonna be?

329
00:25:23,040 --> 00:25:25,940
<i>Pienaar's team played without discipline,</i>

330
00:25:26,370 --> 00:25:30,180
<i>without strategy and without courage.</i>

331
00:25:30,750 --> 00:25:31,530
<i>And therefore...</i>

332
00:25:31,580 --> 00:25:33,340
He's trying to get them to drop me.

333
00:25:33,390 --> 00:25:37,040
He's just bitter because the Springboks
were boycotted when he played.

334
00:25:37,090 --> 00:25:40,140
Maybe, but people listen to
what he says.

335
00:25:40,800 --> 00:25:43,150
<i>they brought shame upon our nation,</i>

336
00:25:43,330 --> 00:25:46,870
<i>and I, for one, can say without fear
of contradiction,</i>

337
00:25:47,520 --> 00:25:52,070
<i>that today, these fifteen so-called men</i>

338
00:25:53,010 --> 00:25:56,640
<i>did not deserve to wear
the hallowed green and gold.</i>

339
00:25:59,890 --> 00:26:01,740
Here's your muti, Madiba.

340
00:26:01,820 --> 00:26:03,720
I warmed the milk tonight.

341
00:26:04,310 --> 00:26:06,340
You're too good to me, Mary.

342
00:26:07,800 --> 00:26:11,130
Your daughter called, to cancel
her visit this weekend.

343
00:26:13,460 --> 00:26:15,150
All right. Did she say why?

344
00:26:15,200 --> 00:26:16,380
No, she didn't.

345
00:26:16,430 --> 00:26:18,780
She said to tell you she was sorry.

346
00:26:19,500 --> 00:26:21,000
I see.

347
00:26:22,980 --> 00:26:25,280
Do you need anything else tonight?

348
00:26:25,950 --> 00:26:28,350
No, Mary. Thank you. I'll go to bed.

349
00:26:28,850 --> 00:26:30,400
Good evening, Tata.

350
00:26:30,730 --> 00:26:32,280
Good evening, Mary.

351
00:26:58,820 --> 00:27:00,980
Hello. There you go.

352
00:27:01,280 --> 00:27:02,680
Oh, yes.

353
00:27:03,270 --> 00:27:05,970
- Some nice pants for you.
- God bless you.

354
00:27:07,550 --> 00:27:08,990
There you go.

355
00:27:09,850 --> 00:27:11,100
There you go.

356
00:27:11,980 --> 00:27:13,480
God bless you.

357
00:27:18,470 --> 00:27:20,270
You're a very lucky boy.

358
00:27:20,680 --> 00:27:23,250
It's a real Springbok practise jersey!

359
00:27:24,360 --> 00:27:28,360
I mean, I know It's a bit big, but
it's warm and it'll last for ever!

360
00:27:29,080 --> 00:27:29,980
C'mon.

361
00:27:30,300 --> 00:27:32,350
C'mon. Take it. It's yours!

362
00:27:34,950 --> 00:27:36,150
Why won't he take it?

363
00:27:36,200 --> 00:27:39,000
If he wears it, the others will beat
him up.

364
00:27:39,340 --> 00:27:41,340
Because the Springboks
are playing so badly?

365
00:27:41,390 --> 00:27:45,460
No. Because, for them, the Springboks
still represent apartheid.

366
00:27:53,450 --> 00:27:56,350
...and now, for the next item
on our agenda.

367
00:27:57,840 --> 00:28:01,820
The NSC executive proposes a vote
on the following motion

368
00:28:03,050 --> 00:28:06,540
that as a prominent symbol
of the apartheid era,

369
00:28:07,230 --> 00:28:12,080
the colors, emblem and the name
of the Springboks

370
00:28:12,680 --> 00:28:15,450
be eliminated immediately

371
00:28:18,450 --> 00:28:21,880
and that all sports teams
representing South Africa

372
00:28:23,480 --> 00:28:28,740
shall be known forthwith as
the Proteas.

373
00:28:30,150 --> 00:28:33,720
Now, Comrades, we will submit
this motion to a hand vote.

374
00:28:34,290 --> 00:28:36,390
In the event of a close count,

375
00:28:37,360 --> 00:28:39,510
we will go to a written ballot.

376
00:28:39,940 --> 00:28:44,020
All those in favor of eliminating
the Springboks,

377
00:28:44,160 --> 00:28:45,260
raise your hands.

378
00:28:45,310 --> 00:28:47,860
Viva! Viva!

379
00:28:47,910 --> 00:28:49,630
Viva Proteas! Viva!

380
00:28:49,760 --> 00:28:52,470
- "Viva!"
- Viva Proteas! Viva!

381
00:28:52,530 --> 00:28:55,800
- "Viva!"
- Viva Proteas! Viva!

382
00:28:55,850 --> 00:28:57,450
- "Viva!"
- Avanza!

383
00:28:57,620 --> 00:28:59,380
"Ole"

384
00:29:04,970 --> 00:29:08,420
Both units to their cars. Right now.

385
00:29:09,310 --> 00:29:13,080
xxx

386
00:29:16,430 --> 00:29:19,060
What do I tell the Japanese
trade delegation?

387
00:29:19,110 --> 00:29:20,820
I delegate that decision to you.

388
00:29:20,870 --> 00:29:22,350
Do you want me to inform the VP?

389
00:29:22,400 --> 00:29:23,180
No.

390
00:29:23,260 --> 00:29:25,700
We should at least include
the Minister of Sport.

391
00:29:25,750 --> 00:29:26,520
No.

392
00:29:26,920 --> 00:29:29,670
I strongly advise against doing this.
Especially on your own.

393
00:29:29,720 --> 00:29:33,000
It gives the impression of autocratic
leadership.

394
00:29:33,050 --> 00:29:36,030
You risk alienating your cabinet
and your party.

395
00:29:36,670 --> 00:29:38,300
Your advice is duly noted.

396
00:29:38,350 --> 00:29:40,770
Madiba, the people want this.

397
00:29:41,040 --> 00:29:44,040
They hate the Springboks. They don't
want to be represented by a team

398
00:29:44,090 --> 00:29:45,580
they cheered against all their lives.

399
00:29:45,630 --> 00:29:48,490
Yes, I know. But in this instance
the people are wrong.

400
00:29:48,540 --> 00:29:52,190
And as their elected leader,
it is my job to show them that.

401
00:29:52,260 --> 00:29:54,630
You're risking your political capital.

402
00:29:54,680 --> 00:29:56,830
You're risking your future as our leader.

403
00:29:56,880 --> 00:30:00,880
The day I am afraid to do that is
the day I am no longer fit to lead.

404
00:30:04,360 --> 00:30:07,960
At least risk it for something
more important than rugby.

405
00:30:08,810 --> 00:30:12,860
Tell the boys that I want to go to
Eersterust, very fast.

406
00:30:25,340 --> 00:30:28,650
We in the executive'd like to applaud you

407
00:30:28,990 --> 00:30:31,960
for your diligence and your courage.

408
00:30:39,590 --> 00:30:41,860
Please, join us in our anthem.

409
00:30:50,680 --> 00:30:55,940
¶ Nkosi sikelel' iAfrika ¶

410
00:30:56,240 --> 00:31:01,550
¶ Maluphakanyisw' uphondo lwayo ¶

411
00:31:01,810 --> 00:31:07,180
¶ Yizwa imithandazo yethu ¶

412
00:31:07,440 --> 00:31:10,520
¶ Nkosi sikelela... ¶

413
00:31:10,570 --> 00:31:13,060
Comrades, comrades, members
of the choir---

414
00:31:13,110 --> 00:31:18,310
we would only interrupt such beautiful
music for something truly important.

415
00:31:18,890 --> 00:31:22,730
Please, welcome, President Mandela!

416
00:31:27,940 --> 00:31:29,040
Thank you.

417
00:31:32,950 --> 00:31:34,090
Thank you.

418
00:31:39,090 --> 00:31:40,190
Thank you.

419
00:31:45,260 --> 00:31:46,960
Why thank you. Please.

420
00:31:49,310 --> 00:31:50,280
Smile.

421
00:31:55,060 --> 00:32:00,380
Brothers, sisters, Comrades,

422
00:32:02,690 --> 00:32:07,670
I am here because I believe
you have made a decision

423
00:32:07,970 --> 00:32:12,740
with insufficient information and
foresight.

424
00:32:13,770 --> 00:32:16,530
I am aware of your earlier vote.

425
00:32:18,520 --> 00:32:22,800
I am aware that it was unanimous.

426
00:32:26,090 --> 00:32:31,070
Nonetheless, I believe we should
restore the Springboks.

427
00:32:35,450 --> 00:32:42,330
Restore their name, their emblem
and their colors, immediately.

428
00:32:45,890 --> 00:32:47,640
Let me tell you why.

429
00:32:48,850 --> 00:32:52,530
On Robben Island, in Pollsmoor Prison,

430
00:32:53,950 --> 00:32:57,250
all of my jailers were Afrikaners.

431
00:32:58,360 --> 00:33:00,110
For twenty seven years,

432
00:33:01,500 --> 00:33:03,000
I studied them.

433
00:33:04,990 --> 00:33:06,840
I learned their language,

434
00:33:08,710 --> 00:33:10,260
I read their books,

435
00:33:11,870 --> 00:33:13,370
their poetry.

436
00:33:14,930 --> 00:33:17,260
I had to know my enemy,

437
00:33:17,610 --> 00:33:20,170
before I could prevail against him.

438
00:33:21,200 --> 00:33:24,120
And we did prevail, did we not?

439
00:33:25,400 --> 00:33:28,600
All of us here we prevailed.

440
00:33:29,410 --> 00:33:32,260
Our enemy is no longer the Afrikaner.

441
00:33:34,500 --> 00:33:37,380
They are our fellow South Africans,

442
00:33:38,310 --> 00:33:41,490
our partners in democracy.

443
00:33:43,240 --> 00:33:47,370
And they treasure Springbok rugby.

444
00:33:50,220 --> 00:33:53,850
If we take that away, we lose them.

445
00:33:55,860 --> 00:34:00,540
We prove that we are what they feared
we would be.

446
00:34:04,090 --> 00:34:06,240
We have to be better than that.

447
00:34:08,130 --> 00:34:10,155
We have to surprise them

448
00:34:11,170 --> 00:34:12,690
with a compassion,

449
00:34:14,110 --> 00:34:15,610
with restraint,

450
00:34:16,720 --> 00:34:18,390
and generosity.

451
00:34:20,350 --> 00:34:21,300
I know.

452
00:34:22,695 --> 00:34:24,990
All of the things they denied us.

453
00:34:26,830 --> 00:34:31,580
But this is no time to celebrate
a petty revenge.

454
00:34:33,530 --> 00:34:35,930
This is the time to build our nation

455
00:34:36,990 --> 00:34:40,150
using every single brick available to
us---

456
00:34:41,530 --> 00:34:44,940
even if that brick comes wrapped in
green and gold.

457
00:34:49,280 --> 00:34:51,600
You elected me your leader.

458
00:34:53,880 --> 00:34:55,480
Let me lead you now.

459
00:34:57,890 --> 00:34:59,640
Who is with me on this?

460
00:35:03,160 --> 00:35:04,660
Who is with me?

461
00:35:19,470 --> 00:35:21,430
Twelve votes.

462
00:35:22,410 --> 00:35:23,370
Twelve!

463
00:35:23,780 --> 00:35:25,280
A luxury.

464
00:35:25,880 --> 00:35:28,470
We only needed one more yes than no.

465
00:35:28,630 --> 00:35:31,050
What if you hadn't got it?

466
00:35:32,010 --> 00:35:35,580
Well, as you know,
that is the parties decision.

467
00:35:36,260 --> 00:35:40,240
I'm sorry, Madiba, but we've got
problems everywhere we look.

468
00:35:40,620 --> 00:35:43,930
Housing, food, jobs,
crime, our currency.

469
00:35:44,680 --> 00:35:48,690
You can't keep interrupting affairs
of state to placate a minority.

470
00:35:48,740 --> 00:35:50,240
But, I must.

471
00:35:51,370 --> 00:35:56,120
That minority still controls the police,
the army, and the economy.

472
00:35:57,800 --> 00:36:00,900
If we lose them we cannot address
the other issues.

473
00:36:02,350 --> 00:36:03,700
So, this rugby,

474
00:36:05,140 --> 00:36:07,840
it's just a political calculation?

475
00:36:11,330 --> 00:36:13,230
It is a human calculation.

476
00:36:15,430 --> 00:36:18,050
If we take away, what they cherish---

477
00:36:18,980 --> 00:36:21,580
the Springboks, their national anthem --

478
00:36:22,650 --> 00:36:26,270
we just reinforce the cycle of fear
between us.

479
00:36:28,470 --> 00:36:31,680
I'll do what I must to break that
cycle.

480
00:36:32,780 --> 00:36:34,660
Or it will destroy us.

481
00:37:02,800 --> 00:37:05,000
This beer tastes like shit, man.

482
00:37:06,020 --> 00:37:07,660
It's not the beer.

483
00:37:10,490 --> 00:37:11,990
Take another.

484
00:37:12,340 --> 00:37:14,040
Everybody take one.

485
00:37:24,350 --> 00:37:26,800
Boys,  I'd like to propose a toast...

486
00:37:28,830 --> 00:37:30,780
To the taste of defeat.

487
00:37:32,080 --> 00:37:33,260
Drink it.

488
00:37:33,660 --> 00:37:34,960
Remember this.

489
00:37:35,490 --> 00:37:38,340
And promise yourself, never to taste
it again.

490
00:37:42,980 --> 00:37:45,280
You're right. It tastes like shit.

491
00:37:52,430 --> 00:37:55,380
Here's the schedule for the
overseas trip.

492
00:37:56,070 --> 00:37:57,570
Let me see.

493
00:38:05,420 --> 00:38:08,080
$ Speaking Afrikaans $

494
00:38:08,740 --> 00:38:10,190
What did he just say?

495
00:38:10,240 --> 00:38:12,600
He asked when we were supposed to sleep.

496
00:38:12,650 --> 00:38:15,210
As well as other basic human functions.

497
00:38:15,530 --> 00:38:16,560
Hey.

498
00:38:17,300 --> 00:38:19,750
If Madiba can do it, we can do it.

499
00:38:28,390 --> 00:38:30,740
In a common struggle

500
00:38:31,760 --> 00:38:35,680
that has brought about our emancipation

501
00:38:36,530 --> 00:38:41,370
and pushed back the frontiers of racism.

502
00:38:42,140 --> 00:38:44,980
The millions of our people

503
00:38:45,950 --> 00:38:49,870
say thank you, and thank you again.

504
00:38:50,330 --> 00:38:52,530
I come here with a message.

505
00:38:52,860 --> 00:38:55,810
<i>People of the Unites States of America:</i>

506
00:38:56,370 --> 00:38:58,470
<i>Open your markets to us.</i>

507
00:38:58,990 --> 00:39:01,970
<i>And come invest in our country.</i>

508
00:39:02,490 --> 00:39:05,860
<i>...and in Japan, President Mandela
met with Japanese officials.</i>

509
00:39:05,910 --> 00:39:08,500
<i>As he concluded a gruelling trip
to the Far East...</i>

510
00:39:08,550 --> 00:39:11,710
And in related news, it was
announced that President Mandela

511
00:39:11,760 --> 00:39:14,240
will visit South Africa this week.

512
00:39:16,050 --> 00:39:17,500
Stop it, old man.

513
00:39:23,380 --> 00:39:25,050
Hey. It's cold, man.

514
00:39:37,540 --> 00:39:39,230
- Morning, Madiba.
- How are you?

515
00:39:39,280 --> 00:39:41,230
- Fine. Thanks.
- Morning, sir.

516
00:39:41,280 --> 00:39:43,000
How is your family, Hendrick?

517
00:39:43,050 --> 00:39:45,250
Top shape, sir. How about yours?

518
00:39:48,950 --> 00:39:50,800
I have a large family.

519
00:39:52,200 --> 00:39:53,700
42 million.

520
00:39:59,270 --> 00:40:01,620
I don't think I'll walk today.

521
00:40:04,050 --> 00:40:05,940
We never, never ask him
about his family.

522
00:40:05,990 --> 00:40:07,910
But he asks about ours all the time.

523
00:40:07,960 --> 00:40:10,950
Think about it, man. He's separated
from his wife, his children...

524
00:40:11,000 --> 00:40:13,240
How often do you see them here, huh?

525
00:40:16,530 --> 00:40:19,680
He's not a saint, okay. He's a man,
with a man's problems

526
00:40:19,730 --> 00:40:22,680
he doesn't need us reminding him
about them.

527
00:40:32,230 --> 00:40:34,730
- Good morning, Madiba.
- Good morning.

528
00:40:35,840 --> 00:40:38,090
- Thank you very much.
- Enjoy it.

529
00:40:44,090 --> 00:40:45,270
Oh, yes.

530
00:40:50,370 --> 00:40:51,870
Very good.

531
00:40:52,660 --> 00:40:54,130
Very good.

532
00:40:59,260 --> 00:41:01,590
- Brenda, good morning.
- Good morning, Madiba.

533
00:41:01,640 --> 00:41:03,140
I like that dress.

534
00:41:03,440 --> 00:41:04,890
Thank you.

535
00:41:05,000 --> 00:41:06,400
This is for you.

536
00:41:07,410 --> 00:41:08,480
What is it?

537
00:41:08,530 --> 00:41:11,580
Your pay checks. You haven't been
collecting them.

538
00:41:14,150 --> 00:41:15,410
What's wrong?

539
00:41:15,500 --> 00:41:17,000
This is terrible.

540
00:41:17,600 --> 00:41:21,400
It's what De Klerk got.
Plus an increase for inflation.

541
00:41:27,240 --> 00:41:29,980
<i>Today, President Mandela announced that,
in his opinion---</i>

542
00:41:30,030 --> 00:41:30,640
Thanks.

543
00:41:30,690 --> 00:41:32,520
<i>---his salary is too high.</i>

544
00:41:32,570 --> 00:41:34,710
Dead right. They're all overpaid.

545
00:41:34,760 --> 00:41:39,110
<i>He has therefore decided to donate
a third of his monthly income to charity.</i>

546
00:41:40,510 --> 00:41:44,380
Give me the houses and cars they give him
and I'll donate a third of my salary too.

547
00:41:44,430 --> 00:41:47,650
- You would not. Not in a million years.
- Pienaar, Hallo.

548
00:41:47,700 --> 00:41:48,710
Hang on a moment, please.

549
00:41:48,760 --> 00:41:51,320
<i>President Mandela said that
he wished to set an example</i>

550
00:41:51,370 --> 00:41:54,870
- to other leaders and Cabinet Ministers.
- Yes. Of course.

551
00:41:55,070 --> 00:41:57,570
- Why thank you. Thank you
- Fat chance.

552
00:41:57,620 --> 00:42:00,290
They're lining their pockets as fast as
they can.

553
00:42:00,340 --> 00:42:02,300
Must be his girlfriend, Nerine...

554
00:42:02,350 --> 00:42:04,400
He knows I'd bloody kill him.

555
00:42:06,760 --> 00:42:07,800
What?

556
00:42:08,300 --> 00:42:09,550
Who was that?

557
00:42:09,980 --> 00:42:13,180
- Well. I told you. It was
his girlfriend. - Shush.

558
00:42:13,910 --> 00:42:15,760
I've been invited to tea.

559
00:42:16,370 --> 00:42:17,520
With who?

560
00:42:17,770 --> 00:42:19,270
The President.

561
00:42:19,600 --> 00:42:21,460
The President of SA Rugby?

562
00:42:21,510 --> 00:42:23,890
Count your fingers after he shakes
your hand, boy.

563
00:42:23,940 --> 00:42:25,440
The President.

564
00:42:29,990 --> 00:42:32,640
He wants me over for tea,
week after next.

565
00:42:35,050 --> 00:42:36,400
Mr. Francois---

566
00:42:37,110 --> 00:42:40,250
you must tell Madiba that
the bus service is very bad,

567
00:42:40,300 --> 00:42:41,670
and too expensive.

568
00:42:41,720 --> 00:42:43,810
He must do something about it.

569
00:42:43,860 --> 00:42:46,660
- Good night everybody.
- Good night, Eunice.

570
00:42:46,830 --> 00:42:48,330
Thank you.

571
00:42:48,630 --> 00:42:51,030
What the hell does he want with you?

572
00:42:53,810 --> 00:42:55,310
I don't know.

573
00:42:55,960 --> 00:42:57,460
<i>What?</i>

574
00:42:59,960 --> 00:43:02,510
Francois, relax. You've met him before.

575
00:43:03,000 --> 00:43:04,720
I shook his hand on the rugby field.

576
00:43:04,770 --> 00:43:06,610
And you didn't even vote.

577
00:43:06,660 --> 00:43:09,310
Come on, Nerine.
He's still the President.

578
00:43:09,420 --> 00:43:11,680
I play rugby. What am I going to say
to the guy?

579
00:43:11,730 --> 00:43:14,180
Say to him, thank you for inviting
me.

580
00:43:15,010 --> 00:43:17,560
What if I pull something stupid in
front of him?

581
00:43:17,610 --> 00:43:20,410
You won't, okay? I'll pick you up
right here.

582
00:43:23,530 --> 00:43:25,330
- Bye.
- Mr. Francois...

583
00:43:26,300 --> 00:43:28,250
Francois, a picture please!

584
00:43:30,390 --> 00:43:32,390
Yeah. Okay. Over here. Okay?

585
00:43:33,260 --> 00:43:35,350
Mr. Pienaar... Mr. Pienaar...

586
00:43:39,730 --> 00:43:41,030
Come on, guys.

587
00:43:49,760 --> 00:43:51,180
See who's coming for tea?

588
00:43:51,230 --> 00:43:53,490
My nephew wants me to get his
autograph.

589
00:43:53,540 --> 00:43:54,730
Who?

590
00:43:54,940 --> 00:43:56,440
Francois Pienaar.

591
00:43:56,860 --> 00:43:58,810
Who wants to escort him in?

592
00:43:59,480 --> 00:44:03,030
- Hey. No autographs, okay?
- I know how to do my job, okay?

593
00:44:04,630 --> 00:44:06,630
Who's this Francois Pienaar?

594
00:44:06,910 --> 00:44:10,310
You can't be serious? He's the captain
of the Springboks.

595
00:44:10,860 --> 00:44:12,420
I like soccer, myself.

596
00:44:12,470 --> 00:44:14,470
Well, you know what they say about
soccer---

597
00:44:14,520 --> 00:44:16,890
It's gentleman's game played by
hooligans.

598
00:44:16,940 --> 00:44:19,720
One the other hand, rugby's a hooligan's
game played by gentlemen.

599
00:44:19,770 --> 00:44:22,120
Ja, ja, I've heard that one before.

600
00:44:22,340 --> 00:44:24,490
It wasn't funny the first time.

601
00:44:26,770 --> 00:44:28,210
Can I ask you a question, Lieutenant?

602
00:44:28,260 --> 00:44:29,760
Yeah, of course.

603
00:44:30,200 --> 00:44:31,700
What's he like?

604
00:44:32,370 --> 00:44:35,860
When I worked for the previous President,
it was my job to be invisible.

605
00:44:35,910 --> 00:44:38,740
This President--- when he found out
I like English toffee

606
00:44:38,790 --> 00:44:41,940
he brought me some back from his
visit in England.

607
00:44:42,020 --> 00:44:44,020
To him, no one's invisible.

608
00:44:45,100 --> 00:44:48,520
That's where you wait. One of his
assistants will come for you.

609
00:44:48,570 --> 00:44:51,160
And the bathroom's over there,
if you need it.

610
00:44:51,210 --> 00:44:52,710
Okay. Thanks.

611
00:44:55,260 --> 00:44:57,400
What are our chances in the World Cup?

612
00:44:57,450 --> 00:44:58,950
I mean, for real.

613
00:45:00,890 --> 00:45:03,490
We'll do our best.
That, I can guarantee.

614
00:45:09,380 --> 00:45:11,180
<i>Office of the President.</i>

615
00:45:17,140 --> 00:45:18,840
So, what is he like?

616
00:45:19,020 --> 00:45:21,620
Well, he's not as big as he looks on TV.

617
00:45:21,910 --> 00:45:25,060
And we don't stand a bloody chance in
the World Cup.

618
00:45:35,190 --> 00:45:36,690
Mr. Pienaar?

619
00:45:36,790 --> 00:45:38,540
Right this way please.

620
00:45:42,480 --> 00:45:43,980
Go in.

621
00:45:45,140 --> 00:45:46,190
Francois,

622
00:45:47,250 --> 00:45:48,550
what an honor.

623
00:45:49,620 --> 00:45:51,120
I'm so excited.

624
00:45:52,010 --> 00:45:53,990
Thank you for coming all this way to
see me.

625
00:45:54,040 --> 00:45:57,070
Yes, sir. Thank you for inviting me,
Mr. President.

626
00:45:57,120 --> 00:45:59,860
So, tell me Francois, how's your
ankle?

627
00:46:00,760 --> 00:46:01,920
My ankle?

628
00:46:01,970 --> 00:46:03,720
I was told it was hurt.

629
00:46:04,240 --> 00:46:05,740
Has it healed?

630
00:46:06,770 --> 00:46:11,230
The truth is, sir, you never really play
at a hundred percent, no matter what.

631
00:46:11,380 --> 00:46:12,880
Ah. Yes.

632
00:46:13,110 --> 00:46:14,960
In sports, as in life, yes?

633
00:46:15,010 --> 00:46:15,760
Yes sir.

634
00:46:15,810 --> 00:46:17,310
Ah. Please, sit.

635
00:46:17,370 --> 00:46:18,870
Take this one.

636
00:46:19,160 --> 00:46:21,610
Looking into the light hurts my
eyes.

637
00:46:24,770 --> 00:46:26,070
Mrs. Brits,

638
00:46:27,090 --> 00:46:29,720
you are a shining light in my day.

639
00:46:29,940 --> 00:46:31,440
Yes sir.

640
00:46:31,620 --> 00:46:35,740
Mrs. Brits, this is Francois Pienaar,
captain of the Springboks.

641
00:46:36,220 --> 00:46:39,420
- Aangename kennis, Mevrou Brits.
- Aangename kennis.

642
00:46:39,840 --> 00:46:41,270
Shall I pour, sir?

643
00:46:41,320 --> 00:46:44,140
No. No. I'd prefer to do it myself.

644
00:46:44,620 --> 00:46:46,770
Thank you very much, Mrs. Brits.

645
00:46:49,490 --> 00:46:51,840
How do you like your tea, Francois?

646
00:46:52,160 --> 00:46:53,660
Just milk, please.

647
00:46:55,740 --> 00:47:00,090
The English have given us many things,
including rugby,

648
00:47:01,670 --> 00:47:06,270
but afternoon tea, that is the greatest.

649
00:47:07,800 --> 00:47:09,300
"Alien."

650
00:47:10,210 --> 00:47:11,710
Thank you, sir.

651
00:47:11,910 --> 00:47:14,230
You have a very difficult job.

652
00:47:15,330 --> 00:47:16,830
I do?

653
00:47:18,540 --> 00:47:20,220
I have a trading business.

654
00:47:20,270 --> 00:47:22,170
Captain of the Springboks.

655
00:47:23,460 --> 00:47:25,770
A very difficult job.

656
00:47:26,840 --> 00:47:29,290
Not compared to yours, Mr. President.

657
00:47:30,370 --> 00:47:34,750
Well, no one's trying to tear my
head off while I'm doing mine.

658
00:47:35,940 --> 00:47:37,380
Yes, sir.

659
00:47:37,440 --> 00:47:38,940
Tell me Francois,

660
00:47:40,220 --> 00:47:42,940
what is your philosophy on leadership.

661
00:47:43,470 --> 00:47:46,320
How do you inspire your team to do
their best?

662
00:47:48,640 --> 00:47:51,940
By example. I've always taught to
lead by example, sir.

663
00:47:52,080 --> 00:47:53,480
Well. That is right.

664
00:47:53,530 --> 00:47:55,360
That is exactly right.

665
00:47:56,110 --> 00:47:59,820
But how to get them to be better than
they think they can be?

666
00:48:01,050 --> 00:48:03,200
That is very difficult, I find.

667
00:48:04,310 --> 00:48:06,110
Inspiration, perhaps.

668
00:48:07,080 --> 00:48:10,210
How do we inspire ourselves to
greatness,

669
00:48:10,470 --> 00:48:12,370
when nothing less will do?

670
00:48:12,850 --> 00:48:15,770
How do we inspire everyone around us?

671
00:48:17,470 --> 00:48:21,000
I sometimes think, it's just by using
the work of others.

672
00:48:23,430 --> 00:48:24,880
On Robben Island,

673
00:48:26,160 --> 00:48:28,310
when things got very bad,

674
00:48:30,230 --> 00:48:32,530
I found inspiration in a poem.

675
00:48:33,280 --> 00:48:34,480
A poem?

676
00:48:34,600 --> 00:48:36,100
A Victorian poem.

677
00:48:38,030 --> 00:48:39,530
Just words.

678
00:48:40,540 --> 00:48:45,730
But they helped me to stand, when
all I wanted to do was to lie down.

679
00:48:49,010 --> 00:48:51,720
But you didn't come all this way
to hear an old man

680
00:48:51,770 --> 00:48:53,460
talk about things that make no sense.

681
00:48:53,510 --> 00:48:55,380
No, no, please, Mr. President.

682
00:48:55,430 --> 00:48:57,530
It makes complete sense to me.

683
00:48:58,160 --> 00:49:00,910
On the day of a big match,
say a test,

684
00:49:02,150 --> 00:49:05,250
in the bus on the way to the stadium,
nobody talks.

685
00:49:05,960 --> 00:49:06,960
Ah. Yes.

686
00:49:07,740 --> 00:49:09,440
They're all preparing.

687
00:49:09,790 --> 00:49:10,940
Right.

688
00:49:11,280 --> 00:49:15,260
But when I think we're ready,
I have the bus driver put on a song

689
00:49:16,300 --> 00:49:18,850
something I've chosen, one we all
know.

690
00:49:20,380 --> 00:49:22,730
And we listen to the words together

691
00:49:24,350 --> 00:49:25,850
and it helps.

692
00:49:27,400 --> 00:49:33,470
I remember when I was invited to the
1992 Olympics in Barcelona.

693
00:49:35,430 --> 00:49:39,180
Everybody in the stadium greeted me
with a song.

694
00:49:40,720 --> 00:49:46,680
At the time the future--- our future---
seemed very bleak.

695
00:49:48,400 --> 00:49:53,900
But to hear that song, and the voices
of people from all over our planet

696
00:49:54,310 --> 00:49:56,810
made me proud to be South African.

697
00:49:58,340 --> 00:50:01,600
It inspired me to come home and do
better.

698
00:50:02,980 --> 00:50:05,940
It allowed me to expect more of myself.

699
00:50:07,670 --> 00:50:09,970
May I ask, what was the song, sir?

700
00:50:10,300 --> 00:50:11,150
Well,

701
00:50:12,390 --> 00:50:14,720
it was Nkosi Sikelel' iAfrika.

702
00:50:16,590 --> 00:50:18,850
A very inspiring song.

703
00:50:20,610 --> 00:50:23,140
We need inspiration, Francois.

704
00:50:24,500 --> 00:50:27,420
Because, in order to build our nation,

705
00:50:28,530 --> 00:50:32,190
we must all exceed our own expectations.

706
00:50:47,520 --> 00:50:49,070
So? What's he like?

707
00:50:50,600 --> 00:50:53,250
He's not like anyone I've ever met
before.

708
00:50:53,550 --> 00:50:55,300
Well? What did he want?

709
00:50:58,750 --> 00:51:00,470
What did you talk about?
You talk about rugby?

710
00:51:00,520 --> 00:51:02,320
What did you talk about?

711
00:51:03,280 --> 00:51:06,880
Francois, it's like talking to a
brick wall. What did he say?

712
00:51:11,700 --> 00:51:14,350
I think he wants us to win the World Cup.

713
00:51:27,180 --> 00:51:28,680
Excuse me.

714
00:51:41,420 --> 00:51:42,920
What do you think?

715
00:51:45,130 --> 00:51:47,120
It doesn't matter what I think.

716
00:51:47,170 --> 00:51:48,670
Yes, it does.

717
00:51:49,640 --> 00:51:51,140
Okay.

718
00:51:51,280 --> 00:51:53,020
I think he looks like one of the
policemen

719
00:51:53,070 --> 00:51:56,270
who forced us out of our house
when you were in jail.

720
00:51:56,610 --> 00:51:59,160
I don't like seeing you shake his hand.

721
00:51:59,220 --> 00:52:01,070
And I'm not the only one.

722
00:52:04,990 --> 00:52:08,540
You criticize without understanding.

723
00:52:09,860 --> 00:52:13,050
You seek only to address your own
personal feelings.

724
00:52:14,430 --> 00:52:16,770
That is selfish thinking, Zindzi.

725
00:52:17,520 --> 00:52:19,600
It does not serve the nation.

726
00:52:23,690 --> 00:52:25,340
Zindzi, wait, please.

727
00:52:27,080 --> 00:52:28,580
Zindzi, I...

728
00:52:31,230 --> 00:52:32,230
Here.

729
00:52:36,020 --> 00:52:37,720
Give this to your mother for me, please.

730
00:52:37,770 --> 00:52:38,960
What is it?

731
00:52:39,470 --> 00:52:42,320
It's a bracelet I found unpacking.

732
00:52:42,830 --> 00:52:45,080
Why don't you just throw it away?

733
00:52:45,780 --> 00:52:48,530
I don't have the right, doesn't
belong to me

734
00:52:50,360 --> 00:52:53,060
If she left it, she meant to throw it
away.

735
00:53:06,850 --> 00:53:09,270
Mrs. Pienaar said you were finished with
the paper.

736
00:53:09,320 --> 00:53:10,620
Ja. Of course.

737
00:53:15,310 --> 00:53:16,850
- Let's go.
- Go. Go.

738
00:53:16,900 --> 00:53:18,130
Hey!

739
00:53:18,230 --> 00:53:19,810
Here we go.

740
00:53:20,300 --> 00:53:21,370
Hit! Yes.

741
00:53:21,430 --> 00:53:24,100
The World Cup is played every four
years.

742
00:53:24,420 --> 00:53:27,170
Sixteen teams qualify from around the
world.

743
00:53:27,480 --> 00:53:29,960
Four pools of four teams,

744
00:53:30,010 --> 00:53:33,320
each playing in nine different
venues around the country.

745
00:53:33,370 --> 00:53:37,450
Two teams will advance from each
pool to the quarter finals.

746
00:53:38,570 --> 00:53:40,470
The Ivory Coast qualifies.

747
00:53:41,320 --> 00:53:42,820
That's wonderful.

748
00:53:43,210 --> 00:53:47,410
According to the experts, we'll reach
the quarter finals, and no further.

749
00:53:47,940 --> 00:53:51,910
According to the experts, you and I
should still be in jail.

750
00:53:56,180 --> 00:53:58,560
<i>You make a personal appearance in
the finals,</i>

751
00:53:58,610 --> 00:54:02,440
<i>and at the opening match between
the Australia and the Springboks.</i>

752
00:54:02,490 --> 00:54:06,890
The finals will be broadcast to over a
billion people around the world, live.

753
00:54:08,790 --> 00:54:10,840
A billion people watching us!

754
00:54:15,050 --> 00:54:17,050
This is a great opportunity.

755
00:54:22,930 --> 00:54:25,470
I reckon you've knocked the stuffing
out of them today.

756
00:54:25,520 --> 00:54:27,220
<i>And now! Come on, boys.</i>

757
00:54:27,270 --> 00:54:28,920
I haven't even begun.

758
00:54:29,570 --> 00:54:30,770
<i>All right. And now...</i>

759
00:54:30,820 --> 00:54:33,970
We may not be the most talented team
in the world...

760
00:54:34,020 --> 00:54:36,670
but sure is we're going to be the
fittest.

761
00:54:37,050 --> 00:54:39,600
- Let's go again, guys.
- Come on, boys.

762
00:54:41,980 --> 00:54:43,680
- Brenda.
- Yes, sir.

763
00:54:44,020 --> 00:54:46,870
Please get the head of South African
rugby for me.

764
00:54:46,920 --> 00:54:48,770
- Right away.
- Thank you.

765
00:54:51,440 --> 00:54:52,840
Yes. Come on.

766
00:54:58,650 --> 00:55:02,140
Guys, listen up! Dr. Ledges wants
a few  words, please.

767
00:55:05,340 --> 00:55:06,840
Afternoon men.

768
00:55:07,380 --> 00:55:09,830
Good to see you all working so hard.

769
00:55:10,220 --> 00:55:12,220
I have a short announcement.

770
00:55:12,370 --> 00:55:15,070
As part of the PR buildup to the
World Cup,

771
00:55:15,320 --> 00:55:19,270
